# ============================================
# ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES - EXAMPLE/TEMPLATE
# ============================================
# 
# This file documents required environment variables for the Weather App.
# Copy this file to create your actual .env file:
# 
#   $ cp .env.example .env
# 
# Then replace placeholder values with your actual API keys.
#
# SECURITY WARNING:
# - .env.example: Safe to commit (no real secrets)
# - .env: NEVER commit to git (contains real API keys)
# 
# The .gitignore file excludes .env from version control.

# ============================================
# WEATHER API CREDENTIALS
# ============================================

# RapidAPI Key for Weather API
# SERVICE: RapidAPI (https://rapidapi.com)
# USED FOR: Fetching weather data for cities
# 
# HOW TO OBTAIN:
# 1. Create account at: https://rapidapi.com/
# 2. Subscribe to Weather API: https://rapidapi.com/weatherapi/api/weatherapi-com
# 3. Go to API dashboard
# 4. Copy "X-RapidAPI-Key" from code snippets
# 5. Paste value here (replace placeholder)
#
# EXAMPLE FORMAT:
# VITE_API_KEY=xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
#
# CURRENT STATUS:
# ✗ This is a PLACEHOLDER - replace with your actual RapidAPI key
# ✓ The actual key should be ~50 characters alphanumeric
VITE_API_KEY=your_rapidapi_key_here

# OpenWeather API Key
# SERVICE: OpenWeatherMap (https://openweathermap.org/api)
# USED FOR: Additional weather data and forecasts
#
# HOW TO OBTAIN:
# 1. Create account at: https://openweathermap.org/
# 2. Navigate to: API Keys section
# 3. Generate new API key
# 4. Wait ~10 minutes for activation
# 5. Paste value here (replace placeholder)
#
# EXAMPLE FORMAT:
# VITE_OPENWEATHER_API_KEY=xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
#
# CURRENT STATUS:
# ✗ This is a PLACEHOLDER - replace with your actual OpenWeather API key
# ✓ The actual key should be 32 characters alphanumeric
VITE_OPENWEATHER_API_KEY=your_openweather_api_key_here

# ============================================
# VARIABLE NAMING: VITE_ PREFIX
# ============================================
#
# WHY "VITE_" PREFIX?
# Vite (our build tool) only exposes environment variables that start with "VITE_"
# This is a SECURITY FEATURE to prevent accidental exposure of secrets.
#
# HOW IT WORKS:
# 1. Variables WITHOUT VITE_ prefix:
#    - Available in Node.js build process
#    - NOT exposed to browser
#    - Example: DATABASE_URL (backend only)
#
# 2. Variables WITH VITE_ prefix:
#    - Exposed to browser JavaScript
#    - Embedded in production bundle
#    - Example: VITE_API_KEY (frontend needs this)
#
# SECURITY IMPLICATIONS:
# ⚠️ VITE_ variables are PUBLIC!
# - Embedded in JavaScript bundle
# - Visible in browser DevTools
# - Can be extracted from source code
# - Anyone with access to your website can see them
#
# BEST PRACTICES:
# ✓ Use VITE_ for: Public API keys, feature flags, API URLs
# ✗ DON'T use VITE_ for: Database passwords, admin secrets, OAuth client secrets
#
# WHY API KEYS IN FRONTEND?
# - Weather APIs require client-side calls
# - OpenWeather supports CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing)
# - RapidAPI allows browser requests
# - Rate limits protect against abuse
# - Free tier usage acceptable for public exposure

# ============================================
# USAGE IN DIFFERENT ENVIRONMENTS
# ============================================
#
# 1. LOCAL DEVELOPMENT:
#    - Create .env file based on this template
#    - Vite loads variables from .env automatically
#    - Access in code: import.meta.env.VITE_API_KEY
#    - Hot reload on changes
#
# 2. DOCKER BUILD:
#    - .env file NOT included in image (excluded by .dockerignore)
#    - Variables passed as build arguments:
#        $ docker build \
#          --build-arg VITE_API_KEY=${VITE_API_KEY} \
#          --build-arg VITE_OPENWEATHER_API_KEY=${VITE_OPENWEATHER_API_KEY} \
#          -t weather-app .
#    - Embedded in static files during 'npm run build'
#
# 3. GITHUB ACTIONS (CI/CD):
#    - Stored as GitHub repository secrets
#    - Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions → New repository secret
#    - Secrets:
#        Name: VITE_API_KEY
#        Value: <your-actual-rapidapi-key>
#        
#        Name: VITE_OPENWEATHER_API_KEY
#        Value: <your-actual-openweather-key>
#    - Referenced in workflow:
#        build-args: |
#          VITE_API_KEY=${{ secrets.VITE_API_KEY }}
#          VITE_OPENWEATHER_API_KEY=${{ secrets.VITE_OPENWEATHER_API_KEY }}
#
# 4. KUBERNETES:
#    - Variables baked into Docker image at build time
#    - NOT runtime environment variables
#    - Image already contains embedded values
#    - No ConfigMaps or Secrets needed for these (already in static files)

# ============================================
# BUILD-TIME vs RUNTIME VARIABLES
# ============================================
#
# VITE ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES ARE BUILD-TIME!
# 
# This is DIFFERENT from traditional backend apps.
#
# BUILD-TIME (Vite/React - THIS APP):
# - Variables read during 'npm run build'
# - Embedded into static JavaScript files
# - Replaced with actual values in code
# - Example:
#     Source code: const key = import.meta.env.VITE_API_KEY;
#     After build: const key = "abc123def456...";
# - Values cannot change without rebuilding
#
# RUNTIME (Backend apps - NOT applicable here):
# - Variables read when application starts
# - Can change without rebuilding
# - Example: Node.js process.env.DATABASE_URL
# - Common for: Database URLs, feature flags
#
# WHY BUILD-TIME FOR FRONTEND?
# - Static files served by nginx (no Node.js runtime)
# - Browser can't access server environment variables
# - Must be embedded in JavaScript
# - Security: Only VITE_ variables embedded (prevents secret leakage)
#
# IMPLICATIONS:
# ✓ Changing API key requires rebuild:
#     $ npm run build  (locally)
#     or
#     Push to git → GitHub Actions rebuilds
# ✗ Cannot change API key by restarting pods
# ✗ Cannot use Kubernetes ConfigMaps for these (already baked in)
# ✓ Faster runtime (no environment variable lookups)
# ✓ Works in static hosting (Netlify, Vercel, S3)

# ============================================
# HOW TO USE THIS FILE
# ============================================
#
# STEP 1: COPY TO .env
# $ cp .env.example .env
#
# STEP 2: EDIT .env WITH REAL VALUES
# $ nano .env
# or
# $ code .env
#
# Replace:
#   VITE_API_KEY=your_rapidapi_key_here
# With:
#   VITE_API_KEY=abc123def456ghi789jkl012mno345pqr678stu901
#
# STEP 3: VERIFY .env EXCLUDED FROM GIT
# $ git status
# Should NOT show .env in "Untracked files"
#
# If .env appears in git status:
# $ echo ".env" >> .gitignore
# $ git add .gitignore
# $ git commit -m "Exclude .env from version control"
#
# STEP 4: START DEVELOPMENT SERVER
# $ npm install
# $ npm run dev
#
# Vite automatically loads .env variables

# ============================================
# ACCESSING VARIABLES IN CODE
# ============================================
#
# CORRECT WAY (Vite):
# const apiKey = import.meta.env.VITE_API_KEY;
# const weatherKey = import.meta.env.VITE_OPENWEATHER_API_KEY;
#
# INCORRECT WAY (Node.js - won't work):
# const apiKey = process.env.VITE_API_KEY;  // ❌ undefined in browser!
#
# TYPE SAFETY (TypeScript):
# Create file: src/vite-env.d.ts
#   interface ImportMetaEnv {
#     readonly VITE_API_KEY: string
#     readonly VITE_OPENWEATHER_API_KEY: string
#   }
#
# EXAMPLE USAGE:
# 
# // src/services/weatherAPI.js
# const API_KEY = import.meta.env.VITE_API_KEY;
# const BASE_URL = 'https://weatherapi-com.p.rapidapi.com';
#
# export async function fetchWeather(city) {
#   const response = await fetch(`${BASE_URL}/forecast.json?q=${city}`, {
#     headers: {
#       'X-RapidAPI-Key': API_KEY,
#       'X-RapidAPI-Host': 'weatherapi-com.p.rapidapi.com'
#     }
#   });
#   return response.json();
# }

# ============================================
# DEBUGGING ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES
# ============================================
#
# CHECK IF VARIABLES LOADED:
# Add to your code (remove before committing!):
# console.log('API Keys loaded:', {
#   rapidapi: !!import.meta.env.VITE_API_KEY,
#   openweather: !!import.meta.env.VITE_OPENWEATHER_API_KEY
# });
#
# COMMON ISSUES:
#
# 1. Variables are undefined:
#    ✗ Missing .env file → Create from .env.example
#    ✗ Missing VITE_ prefix → Rename variable
#    ✗ Typo in variable name → Check spelling
#    ✗ Server not restarted → Restart dev server (Ctrl+C, npm run dev)
#
# 2. Variables work locally but not in Docker:
#    ✗ .env excluded by .dockerignore (correct!)
#    ✗ Forgot --build-arg flags → Pass variables to docker build
#    ✗ Wrong variable names in Dockerfile → Check ARG names match
#
# 3. Variables work in Docker but not in GitHub Actions:
#    ✗ Secrets not configured → Add to repository secrets
#    ✗ Wrong secret names → Check spelling matches workflow
#    ✗ Secrets not passed to build → Check build-args in workflow

# ============================================
# SECURITY BEST PRACTICES
# ============================================
#
# 1. NEVER COMMIT .env:
#    ✓ .env should always be in .gitignore
#    ✓ Check git status before committing
#    ✓ Use git-secrets or gitleaks to scan for leaks
#
# 2. ROTATE API KEYS REGULARLY:
#    ✓ Change keys every 90 days
#    ✓ Rotate immediately if leaked
#    ✓ Use different keys for dev/staging/prod
#
# 3. MONITOR API USAGE:
#    ✓ Check RapidAPI dashboard for unusual activity
#    ✓ Check OpenWeather usage statistics
#    ✓ Set up usage alerts
#    ✓ Rate limits protect against abuse
#
# 4. USE DIFFERENT KEYS PER ENVIRONMENT:
#    ✓ Development: dev-api-key
#    ✓ Staging: staging-api-key
#    ✓ Production: prod-api-key
#    ✓ Helps track usage per environment
#    ✓ Rotate one without affecting others
#
# 5. LIMIT API KEY PERMISSIONS:
#    ✓ RapidAPI: Subscribe only to needed endpoints
#    ✓ OpenWeather: Use only required API products
#    ✓ Set HTTP referrer restrictions if available
#
# 6. WHAT TO DO IF KEY LEAKED:
#    ⚠️ DO NOT panic, but act quickly:
#    1. Immediately revoke/delete compromised key
#    2. Generate new key
#    3. Update .env locally
#    4. Update GitHub secrets
#    5. Rebuild and redeploy (new key embedded in bundle)
#    6. If committed to git:
#       - Remove from git history (git filter-repo)
#       - Force push (WARNING: destructive!)
#       - Notify team
#       - Consider repository as compromised

# ============================================
# TEAM WORKFLOWS
# ============================================
#
# NEW DEVELOPER ONBOARDING:
# 1. Clone repository
# 2. Copy: cp .env.example .env
# 3. Request API keys from team lead
# 4. Paste keys into .env
# 5. Run: npm install && npm run dev
#
# CREATE SHARED TEAM KEYS:
# - Option 1: Team password manager (1Password, LastPass)
# - Option 2: Encrypted internal wiki
# - Option 3: Slack DM (delete after sharing)
# - ❌ NEVER: Email, public Slack channels, commit to git
#
# CONTINUOUS INTEGRATION:
# - GitHub Actions: Use repository secrets
# - GitLab CI: Use CI/CD variables
# - Jenkins: Use credentials plugin
# - CircleCI: Use project environment variables

# ============================================
# ALTERNATIVE: BACKEND PROXY
# ============================================
#
# CURRENT APPROACH:
# Frontend → Directly calls weather APIs
# Pros: Simple, fewer backend requirements
# Cons: API keys visible to users
#
# ALTERNATIVE APPROACH (more secure for sensitive APIs):
# Frontend → Your backend → Weather APIs
#
# IMPLEMENTATION:
# 1. Create backend endpoint:
#      GET /api/weather?city=London
#
# 2. Backend loads API key from environment:
#      const apiKey = process.env.WEATHER_API_KEY;  // No VITE_ prefix!
#
# 3. Backend calls weather API:
#      fetch(`https://api.weatherapi.com/v1/forecast.json?key=${apiKey}&q=${city}`)
#
# 4. Frontend calls your backend:
#      fetch('/api/weather?city=London')
#
# WHEN TO USE BACKEND PROXY:
# ✓ API keys are expensive/sensitive
# ✓ Need to hide API implementation details
# ✓ Want to add caching layer
# ✓ Need to transform API responses
# ✓ Want to aggregate multiple APIs
#
# FOR THIS PROJECT:
# Direct frontend calls are acceptable:
# - Weather APIs designed for frontend use
# - Free/cheap tier usage
# - Rate limits protect against abuse
# - CORS enabled

